column7: none of which involve the abusive and cruel that we witnessed.

column1: 165015;instagram;2018-12-29 01:51:57;FALSE;"first time trying on an old rowing tank since top surgery! i feel great today
column3: but i can't sit here and lie by saying it's all been great. it hasn't.

column1: thankfully i haven't had any physical complications
column2: but post op depression hit me incredibly hard. *all* of my medically related ptsd decided to come up during the first week of recovery. i cried every single day like i was dying and the people around me were worried and scared
column3: but it really just my body remembering that it had been cut into before
column4: in different ways. the flashbacks have died down but i won't ever forget these past two weeks because i started healing from so many more things than just top surgery. slowing down forced me to examine memories i hadn't let myself touch before. i guess it was just one of those times where life makes you do hard work on yourself whether you like it or not. i'm exhausted.

column1: gender confirmation surgery is not a breeze. for a few days i really regretted putting my body through it just because the pain and uncertainty was so bad. i'm starting to enjoy my chest now but i'm seriously reconsidering bottom surgery in the future even though it's something i *desperately* want. trans people pay a huge price to exist as we are and it's not fair that was have to quite literally cause serious injury to our bodies just to not feel suicidal anymore. that's all i really want to say
column2: that it's not fair. i'm absolutely grateful that i had the means at this point in my life to get top surgery
column3: but i just wish i and all of my trans siblings that desire physical transition didn't have to get surgery.

column2: toronto! time to practice! last chance before the new year! how did that happen? this year has been so full i donâ€™t know where to start! from our private city hall wedding in january to our beautiful public wedding in june. the closing of the full time program in april to finding a new home @torontoyogaco in november. the turmoil in the ashtanga yoga world with the #metoo movement
column4: & the general confusion as to where things are going. this year i learned to do things for myself. to make sure that what i was teaching & presenting to my students was authentic & true. to make sure i was standing in my own truth & not something i thought i was supposed to be. and to be transparent about all of it. some decisions have been easy. some have been the hardest iâ€™ve made. some have been life changing. and some have been necessary for life to continue as it is. but all of them have been made from a clear heart & mind. my new yearâ€™s resolution last year (besides lose weight & stop eating sugar ğŸ˜œ) was to be kind
column6: & to find peace. i will continue to strive to live in these states by living in the present. forming my future by learning from my past. and enjoying every moment as it happens. i wish you all every happiness you desire! and for your best year yet! maybe it could start on your mat... doors open at 7am at 1768 danforth ave. see you on the mat. -

column2: i'd rather not. i care about sustainable.  hello keto. :-) #ketoweightloss #ketotransformation #ketofam #ketonewbie #ketofamily #ketolifestyle #keto #metoo

column4: in response to a traumatic situation.  in all other ways i was/am a type a personality

column3: i got to the point where it no longer worked for me and i wanted to be healthy
column5: and let's face it...thin. (clothes!) but what i have learned is that i have to find that determination
column7: within me.  i went about my weight loss like a business project.  hire the right people and they will get me there.  trainers
column9: coaches.  but it didn't work.  i tried to out workout my bad eating habits.  guess what?  does not work.  i tried to get someone else to be motivated for me.  does not work.

column1: i have to do the work.  all of it.  and news flash (to me
column2: not you!) it is so much more fun when it comes from within.  so here i am after trying for so long in all the wrong ways
column3: finally ready and doing the work.  okay

column1: the past few months have been hard. just when i thought i would be on track again i would have another stressful life event. i find the honesty i have on this account to be therapeutic. so i'm going to be honest about three of the things that have kept me away. i'm feeling better about them and am ready to share

i'm not ok with being alone. after a rocky year relationship-wise i need to be by myself and that scares the shit out of me. i need to learn to self-soothe and be compassionate towards myself and it's so hard for me. i comfort myself with food as a substitute for self-love. i don't let on
column2: but i truly hate myself and was working on it in therapy with a bad therapist (my new therapist is encouraging me to go to the professional association with a complaint). luckily i've found a new therapist who is wonderful and i think she will be able to finally help me love myself.

column1: in november i was the victim of a violent sexual assault. i comforted myself with food. i am just now starting to talk about it openly and process what happened in a healthier way. but that derailed my life for a while. i'm going to be ok though
i took a hard look at my finances and i can't afford my gym membership or current lifestyle. i am leaving my home
column3: sending my cat to live with my mom
column4: and buying a used elliptical once the move is over. it will be a complete lifestyle shift but with the debt i accumulated when i was mentally ill and couldn't work
column5: it's necessary. i was really upset about it at first but i feel at peace with it now.

column1: 2018 was a year of upheaval. 2019 will be me changing my home
column5: and my relationship with myself. the circumstances made a lot of the changes happen at once but i'm ok with it. i'm ready to take it on. i've cocooned for a few weeks and i'm ready to take the shaky first steps as i unfurl my wings and learn to fly on my own. here's to confronting changes head on ğŸ¦‹

column1: the past few months have been hard. just when i thought i would be on track again i would have another stressful life event. i find the honesty i have on this account to be therapeutic. so i am going to be honest about three of the things that have kept me away. i am feeling better about them and am ready to share

i am not ok with being alone. after a rocky year relationship-wise i need to be by myself and that scares the shit out of me. i need to learn to self-soothe and be compassionate towards myself and it is so hard for me. i comfort myself with food as a substitute for self-love. i do not let on
column2: but i truly hate myself and was working on it in therapy with a bad therapist (my new therapist is encouraging me to go to the professional association with a complaint). luckily i have found a new therapist who is wonderful and i think she will be able to finally help me love myself.

column1: in november i was the victim of a violent sexual assault. i comforted myself with food. i am just now starting to talk about it openly and process what happened in a healthier way. but that derailed my life for a while. i am going to be ok though
i took a hard look at my fices and i can not afford my gym membership or current lifestyle. i am leaving my home
column3: sending my cat to live with my mom
column4: and buying a used elliptical once the move is over. it will be a complete lifestyle shift but with the debt i accumulated when i was mentally ill and couldn't work
column5: it is necessary. i was really upset about it at first but i feel at peace with it now.

column2: he is also currently under investigation by the met police in london in relation to sexual assault allegations.
